In article <LF5GBLES@math.fu-berlin.de>, jiri@kirk.chemie.fu-berlin.de (Jiri Pittner) writes:
+4) All these 'user-level' wipes rely on the assumption, that if new content
+   is written into any file, its old data blocks are overwritten and not just
+   freed and new ones allocated. Several people replied on my old posting
+   telling that this assumption is true, but
+   Why does not exist a system call wipe(int fd) in Unix? Everything would be
+   much simpler (for appl. programers, of course)!

The assumption about new data overwriting the old data in the same
disk blocks is false for log-structured filesystems (aka journaling
FS).

